---
// First-orientation section. The reader has read the banner and now
// needs a one-paragraph answer to "what does this thing actually do?"
// Concrete example, no marketing.
---

<section id="what" class="container-wide mt-20 scroll-mt-24" aria-labelledby="what-h">
  <div class="grid gap-10 md:grid-cols-[1fr_1.4fr]">
    <header>
      <p class="eyebrow">01 — What rote does</p>
      <h2 id="what-h" class="h-section mt-3">
        The cache that figures out for itself what's safe to cache
      </h2>
    </header>
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <p class="text-base text-[var(--color-ink-soft)]">
        You're editing <code>analyze.py</code>. The script loads a CSV, builds features, fits
        a model, plots a figure. Each run takes a few minutes. You tweak one line in the
        plotting step, save, rerun — and plain Python re-does every step from the top.
      </p>
      <p class="text-base text-[var(--color-ink-soft)]">
        <code>rote</code> watches the script run, decides which function calls are slow and
        safe to remember, writes their return values to disk, and on the next run returns
        those values instead of recomputing them. Edit the plot function and only it
        re-runs; upstream stages come from the cache. Edit something deep in the stack and
        everything downstream re-runs; everything else is reused.
      </p>
      <p class="text-base text-[var(--color-ink-soft)]">
        No decorators required, no annotations. <code>rote run analyze.py</code> rewrites
        the script's AST in memory to wrap every function, then executes the rewritten
        code. Your source file isn't touched. The cache lives at <code>.rote/</code> in
        the working directory.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
